<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        ← All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers · 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        EV Charging and Selling Your Brisbane Home: What Modern Buyers Expect
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Electric vehicle ownership has moved from niche to mainstream in Brisbane's inner east. For sellers in 2027, charging infrastructure is now a buyer-screening feature, not a future consideration.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Electric vehicles now account for a significant share of new car sales in Australia, and the buyers walking through your Brisbane open home are increasingly evaluating the property against their charging needs. This shift has been particularly pronounced in Brisbane's inner east, where EV ownership tracks ahead of the city average thanks to higher household incomes, shorter commuting distances, and a concentration of garage-equipped homes. Five years ago, EV charging was a niche consideration that most buyers never thought about. In 2027, it is a screening criterion: a property without viable charging infrastructure drops off the shortlist of a meaningful slice of the buyer pool, regardless of how good everything else about the home is.</p>

      <p>The practical question for sellers is not whether EV charging matters to buyers. It clearly does. The question is how much to invest in charging infrastructure before listing, how to position what the property already has, and where the line sits between a feature that returns multiples of its cost and an over-investment that will not be recovered at sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The three main types of home charging</h2>
      <p>There are three tiers of home charging, and buyers understand the difference well enough that sellers should too. Level 1 charging is a standard 10-amp power point, the kind already present in most garages. It delivers around 10 kilometres of range per hour, which is slow but adequate for a car that drives under 50km per day and sits overnight. It requires no installation and no new wiring. The downside is the speed: an EV owner relying on level 1 needs to leave the car plugged in for long stretches to keep it usable.</p>

      <p>Level 2 charging is a dedicated wall-mounted charger installed on a 32-amp circuit. It delivers 40 to 60 kilometres of range per hour, which is enough to fully recharge most EVs overnight. Installation requires a licensed electrician and usually a new circuit from the switchboard to the garage. A typical level 2 install in Brisbane sits between $1,500 and $3,500 including the charger itself and the electrical work. This is the baseline expectation for most buyers considering an EV purchase in 2027, and the presence of a level 2 charger is the single clearest indicator to a buyer that the property is genuinely EV-ready.</p>

      <p>Three-phase charging is the fastest home option, available in homes that have three-phase power at the switchboard. It delivers charging rates well above what level 2 provides and is particularly valued by owners of higher-end EVs with larger batteries. Three-phase power is less common in older Brisbane homes but is standard in many newer builds and in some Queenslander conversions where the main switchboard has been upgraded. A three-phase capable home with a charger installed is a premium feature for a specific slice of the buyer pool.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers evaluating a property will look for</h2>
      <p>The strongest selling point is an existing wall charger in the garage or carport, installed properly and visibly in place. Buyers evaluating a property with a level 2 charger already installed do not need to think about the cost, disruption, or availability of an install in the future. They can plug the car in on settlement day. This removes a friction point that would otherwise sit in the buyer's mind through the purchase decision.</p>

      <p>Second best is a dedicated circuit to the garage that is ready for a charger install, even if the charger itself is not in place. A buyer's electrician can confirm the circuit is adequate and fit a unit for a few hundred dollars in labour, with a charger head selected to the buyer's preference. Properties marketed as having a pre-run dedicated circuit tend to attract EV-aware buyers in the same way as a fully installed setup, at lower upfront cost to the seller.</p>

      <p>Beyond the electrical supply, buyers evaluate the physical parking arrangement. Adequate off-street parking that supports EV charging matters: a property with only street parking or heavily constrained driveway access is a significantly weaker proposition for an EV owner than one with a lockable garage or a covered carport with clear access to the switchboard. Solar PV with the generation capacity to run a home charger during daylight hours is increasingly a complementary feature, particularly for buyers planning larger EVs or two-EV households.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The premium buyers will pay</h2>
      <p>A properly installed level 2 charger typically adds $3,000 to $6,000 to a Brisbane home's perceived value, more than the install cost for a well-executed setup. The uplift is larger on properties likely to sell to EV-aware buyers, which in Brisbane's inner east means most family homes above $1.2 million. The uplift is smaller on properties more likely to sell to tradie-led buyers, retirees, or owner-occupiers whose vehicle preferences sit in other categories.</p>

      <p>Three-phase charging adds a further premium on properties where the three-phase supply itself is a selling point: larger homes, workshop-equipped properties, and homes where a high-end EV or two-EV household is part of the likely buyer profile. The premium is less consistent than level 2 but can be substantial on the right property, particularly when paired with a solar system sized to offset the charging load.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers without EV infrastructure should do</h2>
      <p>At minimum, identify the garage or carport power supply and include a clear note in the marketing material describing what the property will support. A statement along the lines of "garage wired for EV charger install, 32-amp circuit available from main switchboard" gives an EV buyer the information they need to proceed with confidence, without the seller needing to install anything. Where the circuit is not yet present, a statement describing what would be required ("switchboard has capacity for a new 32-amp circuit to the garage, typical install cost $1,500-$2,500") is also useful. Specificity builds buyer trust; vague references to "EV potential" do not.</p>

      <p>If the circuit is already available and the property is targeting an EV-aware buyer segment, consider installing a basic level 2 charger before listing. The $1,500 to $3,500 spend is recovered several times over in sale price for most inner Brisbane homes above $1.2 million, and the charger becomes a concrete feature in the photos and listing material. If the circuit is not yet available and running one would require a major switchboard upgrade, the cost-benefit becomes less clear. In that case, presenting the property honestly as "not currently EV-ready but with straightforward upgrade path" is better than avoiding the topic.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to avoid</h2>
      <p>Do not attempt a DIY wall charger install. Domestic 32-amp circuits carry enough current to be dangerous, and an install by anyone other than a licensed electrician is non-compliant with Australian wiring standards. The buyer's electrician or building inspector will identify an unprofessional install immediately, which turns a potential selling point into a disclosure problem. Always use a licensed electrician, obtain the compliance paperwork, and keep the documentation for handover to the buyer.</p>

      <p>Do not advertise the property as "EV ready" if the switchboard or circuit capacity cannot actually support a charger install without significant upgrades. The claim will be tested by the buyer's electrician, and a mismatch between the marketing and the reality undermines trust at exactly the point in the sale where trust matters most. If the property needs a switchboard upgrade before a level 2 charger can be fitted, say so in the listing. Buyers accept this information and factor it into their offer. What they do not accept is discovering the constraint during their own pre-purchase inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Solar and EV charging together</h2>
      <p>Buyers considering a larger or premium EV increasingly want solar generation sized to run the vehicle charging during daylight hours. The current benchmark for a home positioned as fully EV-ready is a 6 to 10 kilowatt solar system combined with a level 2 wall charger and, where possible, a home battery to time-shift charging into off-peak windows. This combination sits above the minimum expectation and is worth highlighting on properties where it is in place. On properties with solar but no charger, the solar itself still supports the EV narrative, and adding a charger before listing completes the package at a relatively modest cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical positioning</h2>
      <p>If the property has EV charging, make it a marketing feature. Photograph the charger in situ, include the unit's kilowatt rating in the listing, mention any associated solar or battery capacity, and ensure the property description addresses charging explicitly rather than burying it in a features list. For a share of the Brisbane buyer pool that is growing quickly year on year, this is now a meaningful differentiator: the kind of detail that moves a property from the "consider" pile into the "inspect this weekend" pile. The investment required to reach this position is small relative to the overall selling cost, and the return on a well-chosen level 2 install is consistently positive on Brisbane's inner east properties at 2027 market levels.</p>

